\section{The Topological Susceptibility \label{topsusapp}}
In this appendix we calculate the topological susceptibility. This we
calculate by allowing a non-vanishing vacuum angle $\theta$ and
subsequently projecting onto sectors of fixed topological charge by
means of a Fourier transform. We consider the classes of symmetry
breaking separately.

The case of $\beta=2$ has been considered previously \cite{D01} by means
of the same method as we will use here. The result found was
\begin{eqnarray}
\left<\nu^2\right>_{\beta=2} & = & \frac{m_0^2VF^2}{2N_c}.
\label{topsus2}
\end{eqnarray}

Matching of the two finite volume regimes requires that the dependence
of the topological susceptibility upon the Dyson index follows the
same pattern as the last (non-trivial) part of the diagonal
propagator.  Thus we expect the topological susceptibility to be twice as
large as formula (\ref{topsus2}) in the $\beta=1$ case while being
identically the same in the $\beta=4$ case.

\subsection{$\beta=1$}
A non-vanishing vacuum angle can be absorbed into the mass-matrix
$\cal M$ by letting ${\cal M}\to e^{i\theta/N_f}{\cal M}$ \cite{LS92, SV95}.  We
can include the vacuum angle in a shifted $\Xi_0$. To see this
consider how the change of the mass matrix affects the combination
\begin{eqnarray}
\mbox{Re}{\rm Tr}{\cal M} U^\dag \! \to \! \mbox{Re}{\rm Tr}\left[{\cal M} e^{i\theta/N_f}
e^{-i\sqrt{2}\xi/F_1}e^{-i\sqrt{2}\varphi_0/F_1}\right]\!\!,
\end{eqnarray}
from which we find that we can include the vacuum angle in a change of
variables
\begin{eqnarray}
\varphi_0 & \to & \varphi_0-\frac{\theta F_1}{\sqrt{2}N_f}.
\end{eqnarray}
Taking the trace of this equation we obtain (note that the dimension
of the coset is $2N_f\times 2N_f$)
\begin{eqnarray}
\Xi_0 \to  \Xi_0' \equiv \Xi_0-\sqrt{2}\theta F_1.
\end{eqnarray}

Finally we perform the Fourier transform (for large volumes)
\begin{widetext}
\begin{eqnarray}
{\cal Z}^{\beta=1}_\nu & = & \frac{1}{2\pi}\int_{-\pi}^{\pi}d\theta e^{-i\nu\theta}
\int_{SU(2N_f)/Sp(2N_f)}dU_0 \exp\left[\frac{1}{2}{\rm Tr}{\cal M}(U_0+U_0^\dag)
-\frac{m_0^2V}{2N_c}\Xi_0'^2\right] \nonumber \\
& \propto & \sqrt{\frac{N_c}{2m_0^2VF_1^2}}e^{-\nu^2N_c/4m_0^2VF_1^2}
\int_{U(2N_f)/Sp(2N_f)}dU_0 (\det U_0)^{-\nu/2}
\exp\left[\frac{1}{2}{\rm Tr}{\cal M}(U_0+U_0^\dag)\right],
\end{eqnarray}
\end{widetext}
from which we identify the topological susceptibility
\begin{eqnarray}
\left<\nu^2\right> & = & \frac{2m_0^2VF_1^2}{N_c} = \frac{m_0^2VF^2}{N_c}.
\end{eqnarray}
As expected, this is exactly twice the result from the $\beta=2$ case.

\subsection{$\beta=4$}
The $\beta=4$ calculation proceeds in the same way. In this case the
vacuum angle can be included in the mass matrix by letting ${\cal M}\to
e^{i\theta/N_cN_f}{\cal M}$ \cite{LS92, SV95}. Again this can be included in the
field of constant modes, this time by the substitution
\begin{eqnarray}
\varphi_0 & \to & \varphi_0-\frac{\theta F_4}{\sqrt{2}N_cN_f}.
\end{eqnarray}
Thus for the traced equation we find
\begin{eqnarray}
\Xi_0 \to \Xi_0' \equiv \Xi_0-\frac{\theta F_4}{\sqrt{2}N_c}.
\end{eqnarray}
The projection onto sectors of fixed topological charge is performed as
before
\begin{widetext}
\begin{eqnarray}
{\cal Z}^{\beta=4}_\nu & = & \frac{1}{2\pi}\int_{-\pi}^{\pi}d\theta e^{-i\nu\theta}
\int_{SU(N_f)/SO(N_f)}dU_0 \exp\left[\frac{1}{2}{\rm Tr}{\cal M}(U_0+U_0^\dag)
-\frac{m_0^2V}{2N_c}\Xi_0'^2\right] \nonumber \\
& \propto & \sqrt{\frac{1}{\left<\bar\nu^2\right>}}e^{-\bar\nu^2/2\left<
\bar\nu^2\right>}
\int_{U(N_f)/SO(N_f)} dU_0 (\det U_0)^{-\bar\nu}
\exp\left[\frac{1}{2}{\rm Tr}{\cal M}(U_0+U_0^\dag)\right],
\end{eqnarray}
\end{widetext}
with the topological susceptibility given by
\begin{eqnarray}
\left<\bar\nu^2\right> & = & \frac{m_0^2VF_4^2}{2N_c} = \frac{m_0^2VF^2}{2N_c}.
\end{eqnarray}
Again we define $\bar\nu\equiv N_c\nu$. This result is also as expected.

